article.description: Two-time defending national champion UConn is starting to play like a team intent on winning three in a row.
article.headline: Huskies limit Knights to 10 first-half points
article.linkText: UConn hands Rutgers first home loss of season
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- Two-time defending national champion
Connecticut is starting to play like a team intent on winning three
in a row.

Barbara Turner outscored Rutgers 12-10 in the first half, and
Connecticut (No. 1 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) put on a defensive clinic in rolling to its ninth
straight victory, 66-43 on Saturday night.

"I think we have a certain kind of focus right now," Turner
said after scoring a career-high 27 points on 12-for-15 shooting.
"There are a lot of people talking about a lot of other teams in
the country and they are not talking about us as much as they did
last year. So we just have that focus and mind-set now and we're
using that to carry us on from now till."

The Huskies (20-2, 10-1 Big East) came into this game with a
little extra motivation. Warming up before the game, a Scarlet
Knights band member held up a picture of distraught Connecticut
players on the bench here after Villanova beat them in the
conference championship last year to end a 70-game winning streak.

"We came into the locker room and sat in the same seats we sat
in last year and all had the same feeling," Turner said. "It was
a different focus. We were ready to come out and play. We had heard
about how good they were, and we were ready to come out and see how
good they were."

The Scarlet Knights (14-9, 6-5) had a horrible first half in
losing for the first time at home in 12 games this season. They hit
just four 27 shots in falling behind 34-10.

The 10 first-half points allowed were one shy of Connecticut's
conference-record low, set in December 2001 against St. John's. The
total was three shy of the school record for defense in a half, set
against Loyola of Maryland in 1996.

Had it not been for a basket by Aquisha Cahoe with 26 seconds to
go, Connecticut would have had three players all outscore Rutgers
in the opening 20 minutes. Jessica Moore had all 10 of her points
in the first half and Ann Strother had nine of her 15.

"I think we came here in my sophomore year and had a game like
this," said Diana Taurasi, who had 11 points, only two in the big
first half. "I don't know what the halftime score was but it was
similar to this. But when you hold a good team like this to 10,
it's surprising."

When asked if she felt sorry for Rutgers, Taurasi had a quick
answer.

"Nope," said the senior who was the nation's player of the
year last season. "When you work as hard as we do, you don't feel
sorry for anyone."

This was second straight super defensive effort for UConn this
week. The Huskies limited Syracuse to 15 first-half points in an
82-38 win on Wednesday.

Rutgers does not have records for all its games so it is
uncertain whether the first-half point total was a school low.

This is the second time Connecticut embarrassed Rutgers this
season. The Huskies limited the Scarlet Knights to 17 first-half
points on Jan. 19 in a 72-47 win in which Taurasi scored 27 points.

Turner, Moore and Strother carried the load in silencing a
sellout crowd of 7,734 at the Rutgers Athletic Center.

"We were so far out of it our fans couldn't help us," said
Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer, whose team shot 14.8 percent in
the first half.

Moore, who was benched in the Huskies' last visit to New Jersey
in a game against Seton Hall, scored six points in staking
Connecticut to an 8-0 lead.

After missing their first eight shots, Dawn McCullouch, who led
Rutgers with 14 points, finally hit a jumper with 14:51 to go.

Rutgers missed its next eight shots before McCullouch scored on
a drive with 8:03 to play. By that time, Connecticut had built a
21-2 lead and the Huskies were never threatened.

Rutgers star guard Cappie Pondexter was limited to seven points
on 3-for-20 shooting.

"It was a lot of zone," Taurasi said. "We just gave them a
lot of different looks, particularly Cappie."
